                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d550">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.2221/633: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">Then in France, to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">St. Jean de Luz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-11T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 11, 1937—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 11—12:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>391. Your telegram No. B–375, November 10, 11 a.m.<note n="14" xml:id="d550fn14"
                        >Not printed; this telegram informed the Ambassador of the substance of the
                        telegram of November 6, noon, to the Consul at Seville, and his reply of
                        November 9, 2 p.m., <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> In a number of
                    informal conversations with officers civil and military of Franco am assured no
                    Americans will be executed because Salamanca is convinced our neutrality is
                    sincere and there is no desire to embarrass us because of violators of our laws.
                    These assurances were voluntary and applied generally and not to subject matter
                    of your telegram. I am sure we need not worry on that score.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
